git_pretty function can be given a range of commits, and that the CL would be

differently for different versions of git, so I'm not going to miss it again.

include a full range of CLs, and they instead repeat the same one many times.

fiber reconciler. It's mostly a copy-paste of the userspace
implementation, which is not ideal but is a good enough starting place.

The main change we'll want to make to this native implementation is to
move the tearing checks from the layout phase to an earlier, pre-commit
phase so that code that runs in the commit phase always observes a
consistent tree.

from the store.

git_pretty function can be given a range of commits, and that the CL would be

differently for different versions of git, so I'm not going to miss it again.

include a full range of CLs, and they instead repeat the same one many times.

git_pretty function can be given a range of commits, and that the CL would be

differently for different versions of git, so I'm not going to miss it again.

include a full range of CLs, and they instead repeat the same one many times.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 395508116
Change-Id: Ic0e87bedb95893301da37191fc101fbc279e22ef","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MaxMood96/tensorflow/commits/32f82e53099483da528987dd917392bd66c1770f"},{"sha":"86b1d613792d33f7c0d296ff84b11a3dad20faab","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[MLIR][KernelGen] Fix GPU module cache and make it a kernel resource

This fixes a subtle bug in the GPU module caches, which assumed that no two GPU
modules are loaded from the same memory location. When JIT-compiling kernels,
however, this can (and did) happen, which previously lead to a false cache hit,
resulting in the use of an incorrect GPU kernel.

Making the GPU module cache a kernel resource binds its lifetime to that of the
kernel context and also to that of the JIT cache....

Change-Id: Ia8fe5aad4d6d1f95b157ec35b110dba6242d709d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MaxMood96/tensorflow/commits/6cfb888ddd2fe9ca93f1fc63cbdd30dffa6b2627"},{"sha":"a43f1c5e4dc3bd2955df13c844d0d7a6e8eac628","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"When determinism is enabled, raise error in tf.timestamp.

A FailedPrecondition error is raised. InvalidArgument is used for random ops when the seed isn't specified, but that doesn't apply here as there are no arguments.

tf.timestamp is mostly used to seed random ops. It is also occasionally used for measuring the performance of some part of the model. The latter case is a legitimate use case when determinism is used, but we must raise an error to guard against the former case.

[{"sha":"64387f4e027a4e4980a4203cf78a87c3c402c659","author":{"name":"Austin Anderson","email":"3151abf3c4c3b9378c98ede6ff5f755099ce0bdc@google.com"},"message":"Fix buggy original implementation of the sizetracker git version workaround

My original version of this fix last week was a bit buggy; I forgot that the
git_pretty function can be given a range of commits, and that the CL would be
different for each result. This new fix is much simpler, and does not act
differently for different versions of git, so I'm not going to miss it again.

The data is still correct, but results with the original fix do not correctly
include a full range of CLs, and they instead repeat the same one many times.

[{"sha":"082f49f6efe79245424a4173af8cbe132b42487c","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Add test that triggers infinite update loop

In 18, passive effects are flushed synchronously if they are the
result of a synchronous update. We have a guard for infinite update
loops that occur in the layout phase, but it doesn't currently work for
synchronous updates from a passive effect.

The reason this probably hasn't come up yet is because synchronous
updates inside the passive effect phase are relatively rare: you either
have to imperatively dispatch a discrete event, like `el.focus`, or you
have to call `ReactDOM.flushSync`, which triggers a warning. (In
general, updates inside a passive effect are not encouraged.)

I discovered this because `useSyncExternalStore` does sometimes
trigger updates inside the passive effect phase.

This commit adds a failing test to prove the issue exists. I will fix
it in the next commit.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/082f49f6efe79245424a4173af8cbe132b42487c"}]

Change-Id: I9ea999e4a23ce5c63d392d8605029f322d664c45","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sloppyjuicy/tensorflow/commits/a1d58a9f50c594b311c0998429d25d3cc5e392e5"},{"sha":"5e4adb9583a5b1652e33c18ce73c16cfbdab958f","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Rewrite ParallelMapDataset in make_deterministic.

This makes calling Dataset.map deterministic when stateful ops are in the map_fn (assuming the user doesn't pass deterministic=False to map or tf.data.Options).

Unfortunately, this can make a model's input pipeline very very slow when determinism is enabled. For example, on the official resnet50 model with 8 V100s, performance drops from 5199 images/sec to 331 images/sec, making performance only 6% of what it is without determinism. The input pipeline is probably even slower than 6% of it's original speed, as the model is bottlenecked by the GPU without determinism and by the input pipeline with determinism. In the future, I hope to improve performance when determinism is enabled.

Change-Id: I766e734491c6733c5f5bd4a5e7e82da954e3a016","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MaxMood96/tensorflow/commits/26bb0a3e52c74bc47725456753166c7a3a686cc3"},{"sha":"bb588f4b89355d46b10955922bdcf385075d286e","author":{"name":"Allen Lavoie","email":"eb65be0597eb1f51f240bbfc00f1cd10ccd2547c@google.com"},"message":"Allow tf.GradientTape to ignore forward-pass ops downstream of tf.stop_gradient

This will not change the numerics of tf.stop_gradient, just prevent some unneeded tf.function gradients from being built and reduce memory usage executing op-by-op (since tensors downstream of stop_gradient will no longer be `tape.watch`ed and held in memory unless there is another path to them).

Alternatively we could expose a tf.autodiff.stop_recording() context manager or something to that effect. We use that API a decent amount internally to avoid building gradient graphs / holding on to intermediates, so this seems like a good thing let people control one way or another.

[{"sha":"8f96c6b2ac3ff0e38f60c87b1f08deb9993526b5","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"[Bugfix] Prevent infinite update loop caused by a synchronous update in a passive effect (#22277)

* Add test that triggers infinite update loop

In 18, passive effects are flushed synchronously if they are the
result of a synchronous update. We have a guard for infinite update
loops that occur in the layout phase, but it doesn't currently work for
synchronous updates from a passive effect.

The reason this probably hasn't come up yet is because synchronous
updates inside the passive effect phase are relatively rare: you either
have to imperatively dispatch a discrete event, like `el.focus`, or you

trigger updates inside the passive effect phase.

This will not change the numerics of tf.stop_gradient, just prevent some unneeded tf.function gradients from being built and reduce memory usage executing op-by-op (since tensors downstream of stop_gradient will no longer be `tape.watch`ed and held in memory unless there is another path to them).

[{"sha":"225740be4864ee8eeb349b38b329291450245578","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Add named hooks support to react-devtools-inline (#22263)

This commit builds on PR #22260 and makes the following changes:
* Adds a DevTools feature flag for named hooks support. (This allows us to disable it entirely for a build via feature flag.)
* Adds a new Suspense cache for dynamically imported modules. (This allows a component to suspend while importing an external code chunk– like the hook names parsing code).
* DevTools supports a hookNamesModuleLoaderFunction param to import the hook names module. I wish this could be handles as part of the react-devtools-shared package, but I'm not sure how to configure Webpack (4) to serve the chunk from react-devtools-inline. This seemed like a reasonable workaround.

The PR also contains an additional unrelated change:
* Removes pre-fetch optimization (added in DevTools: Improve named hooks network caching #22198). This optimization was mostly only important for cases where sources needed to be re-downloaded, something which we can now avoid in most cases¹ thanks to using cached responses already loaded by the page. (I tested this locally on Facebook and this change has no negative performance impact. There is still some overhead from serializing the JS through the Bridge but that's constant between the two approaches.)

¹ The case where we don't benefit from cached responses is when DevTools are opened after the page has already loaded certain scripts. This seems uncommon enough that I don't think it justified the added complexity of prefetching.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jstejada/react/commits/225740be4864ee8eeb349b38b329291450245578"},{"sha":"96814e71b2ec13af64cd2670c9e69ab982ab2951","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Revert Suspense cache Thenable.catch() change (#22280)

PiperOrigin-RevId: 395508116
Change-Id: Ic0e87bedb95893301da37191fc101fbc279e22ef","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/32f82e53099483da528987dd917392bd66c1770f"},{"sha":"86b1d613792d33f7c0d296ff84b11a3dad20faab","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[MLIR][KernelGen] Fix GPU module cache and make it a kernel resource

This fixes a subtle bug in the GPU module caches, which assumed that no two GPU
modules are loaded from the same memory location. When JIT-compiling kernels,
however, this can (and did) happen, which previously lead to a false cache hit,
resulting in the use of an incorrect GPU kernel.

Making the GPU module cache a kernel resource binds its lifetime to that of the
kernel context and also to that of the JIT cache....

Change-Id: Ia8fe5aad4d6d1f95b157ec35b110dba6242d709d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/6cfb888ddd2fe9ca93f1fc63cbdd30dffa6b2627"},{"sha":"a43f1c5e4dc3bd2955df13c844d0d7a6e8eac628","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"When determinism is enabled, raise error in tf.timestamp.

A FailedPrecondition error is raised. InvalidArgument is used for random ops when the seed isn't specified, but that doesn't apply here as there are no arguments.

tf.timestamp is mostly used to seed random ops. It is also occasionally used for measuring the performance of some part of the model. The latter case is a legitimate use case when determinism is used, but we must raise an error to guard against the former case.

* Add test that triggers infinite update loop

In 18, passive effects are flushed synchronously if they are the
result of a synchronous update. We have a guard for infinite update
loops that occur in the layout phase, but it doesn't currently work for
synchronous updates from a passive effect.

The reason this probably hasn't come up yet is because synchronous
updates inside the passive effect phase are relatively rare: you either
have to imperatively dispatch a discrete event, like `el.focus`, or you
have to call `ReactDOM.flushSync`, which triggers a warning. (In
general, updates inside a passive effect are not encouraged.)

I discovered this because `useSyncExternalStore` does sometimes
trigger updates inside the passive effect phase.

This commit adds a failing test to prove the issue exists. I will fix
it in the next commit.

* Fix failing test added in previous commit

The way we detect a "nested update" is if there's synchronous work
remaining at the end of the commit phase.

Currently this check happens before we synchronously flush the passive
effects. I moved it to after the effects are fired, so that it detects
whether synchronous work was scheduled in that phase.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jstejada/react/commits/8f96c6b2ac3ff0e38f60c87b1f08deb9993526b5"}]

[{"sha":"64387f4e027a4e4980a4203cf78a87c3c402c659","author":{"name":"Austin Anderson","email":"3151abf3c4c3b9378c98ede6ff5f755099ce0bdc@google.com"},"message":"Fix buggy original implementation of the sizetracker git version workaround

My original version of this fix last week was a bit buggy; I forgot that the
git_pretty function can be given a range of commits, and that the CL would be
different for each result. This new fix is much simpler, and does not act
differently for different versions of git, so I'm not going to miss it again.

The data is still correct, but results with the original fix do not correctly
include a full range of CLs, and they instead repeat the same one many times.

Creates new subtree tag, PassiveStatic, that represents whether a
tree contains any passive effect hooks.

It corresponds to the PassiveStatic effect tag, which represents the
same concept for an individual fiber.

This allows us to remove the PassiveStatic effect tag from PassiveMask.
Its presence was causing us to schedule a passive effect phase callback
on every render, instead of only when something changed. That's now
fixed; this is reflected in the SchedulerProfiler tests.

Change-Id: I9ea999e4a23ce5c63d392d8605029f322d664c45","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/GesuPlace/tensorflow/commits/a1d58a9f50c594b311c0998429d25d3cc5e392e5"},{"sha":"5e4adb9583a5b1652e33c18ce73c16cfbdab958f","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Rewrite ParallelMapDataset in make_deterministic.

This makes calling Dataset.map deterministic when stateful ops are in the map_fn (assuming the user doesn't pass deterministic=False to map or tf.data.Options).

Unfortunately, this can make a model's input pipeline very very slow when determinism is enabled. For example, on the official resnet50 model with 8 V100s, performance drops from 5199 images/sec to 331 images/sec, making performance only 6% of what it is without determinism. The input pipeline is probably even slower than 6% of it's original speed, as the model is bottlenecked by the GPU without determinism and by the input pipeline with determinism. In the future, I hope to improve performance when determinism is enabled.

git_pretty function can be given a range of commits, and that the CL would be
different for each result. This new fix is much simpler, and does not act
differently for different versions of git, so I'm not going to miss it again.

include a full range of CLs, and they instead repeat the same one many times.

Change-Id: Ic0e87bedb95893301da37191fc101fbc279e22ef","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/abhip07/tensorflow/commits/32f82e53099483da528987dd917392bd66c1770f"},{"sha":"86b1d613792d33f7c0d296ff84b11a3dad20faab","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[MLIR][KernelGen] Fix GPU module cache and make it a kernel resource

This fixes a subtle bug in the GPU module caches, which assumed that no two GPU
modules are loaded from the same memory location. When JIT-compiling kernels,
however, this can (and did) happen, which previously lead to a false cache hit,
resulting in the use of an incorrect GPU kernel.

Making the GPU module cache a kernel resource binds its lifetime to that of the
kernel context and also to that of the JIT cache....

Change-Id: Ia8fe5aad4d6d1f95b157ec35b110dba6242d709d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/abhip07/tensorflow/commits/6cfb888ddd2fe9ca93f1fc63cbdd30dffa6b2627"},{"sha":"a43f1c5e4dc3bd2955df13c844d0d7a6e8eac628","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"When determinism is enabled, raise error in tf.timestamp.

A FailedPrecondition error is raised. InvalidArgument is used for random ops when the seed isn't specified, but that doesn't apply here as there are no arguments.

tf.timestamp is mostly used to seed random ops. It is also occasionally used for measuring the performance of some part of the model. The latter case is a legitimate use case when determinism is used, but we must raise an error to guard against the former case.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 395537793
Change-Id: I9ea999e4a23ce5c63d392d8605029f322d664c45","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/abhip07/tensorflow/commits/a1d58a9f50c594b311c0998429d25d3cc5e392e5"},{"sha":"5e4adb9583a5b1652e33c18ce73c16cfbdab958f","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Rewrite ParallelMapDataset in make_deterministic.

This makes calling Dataset.map deterministic when stateful ops are in the map_fn (assuming the user doesn't pass deterministic=False to map or tf.data.Options).

Unfortunately, this can make a model's input pipeline very very slow when determinism is enabled. For example, on the official resnet50 model with 8 V100s, performance drops from 5199 images/sec to 331 images/sec, making performance only 6% of what it is without determinism. The input pipeline is probably even slower than 6% of it's original speed, as the model is bottlenecked by the GPU without determinism and by the input pipeline with determinism. In the future, I hope to improve performance when determinism is enabled.

Creates new subtree tag, PassiveStatic, that represents whether a
tree contains any passive effect hooks.

It corresponds to the PassiveStatic effect tag, which represents the
same concept for an individual fiber.

This allows us to remove the PassiveStatic effect tag from PassiveMask.
Its presence was causing us to schedule a passive effect phase callback
on every render, instead of only when something changed. That's now
fixed; this is reflected in the SchedulerProfiler tests.

(The naming is getting really confusing. as if it accepts the first node of a child list. This is likely because
the function was based on similar functions like
`flushPassiveUnmountEffects`, which do accept a child list.

Unfortunately, types don't help here because we use the first node
in the list to represent the whole list, so in both cases, the type
is Fiber.

fibers instead of a child list, to help avoid confusion.

Don't set image on containerd container.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/afxcn/moby/commits/49e809fbfe250f3df2deacc0c3e5c403db3b8915"},{"sha":"1bb3491601a4f1d654edbc1e997016baa015176e","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"builder: fix detection of experimental --stream option (deprecated)

Commit 6ca3ec88ae9e1435abbed665ec598c00058659da deprecated the experimental
"--stream" option for the legacy builder, adding an error message is a client
attempted to use this feature.

However, the detection used the session-ID (`session=xxx` query parameter),
which happens to be set automatically by the CLI if it detects that the daemon
has session support. Because of this, builds fail when trying to perform them
on a daemon with the `--experimental` flag set.

This patch changes the detection to look for the `remote` query parameter, which
is set to "client-session" when using the `--stream` option with the classic
(non-Buildkit) builder.

Before this change, running `docker build` with an older (19.03 or older) cli
against a daemon with `--experimental` enabled caused an error:

    $ dockerd --experimental &
    $ docker pull docker:18.09
    $ docker run -it --rm -v /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock docker:18.09 sh -c 'echo "FROM scratch" | docker build -'

    Sending build context to Docker daemon  2.048kB
    Error response from daemon: experimental session with v1 builder is no longer supported, use builder version v2 (BuildKit) instead

    docker run -it --rm -v /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock -w /foo docker:18.09 sh -c 'echo "FROM scratch" > Dockerfile && docker build --stream .'
    Error response from daemon: experimental session with v1 builder is no longer supported, use builder version v2 (BuildKit) instead

With this patch, the error only occurs when trying to use the experimental
`--stream` option:

    $ dockerd --experimental &
    $ docker pull docker:18.09
    $ docker run -it --rm -v /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock docker:18.09 sh -c 'echo "FROM scratch" | docker build -'

    Step 1/1 : FROM scratch
     --->
    No image was generated. Is your Dockerfile empty?

    $ docker run -it --rm -v /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock -w /foo docker:18.09 sh -c 'echo "FROM scratch" > Dockerfile && docker build --stream .'

    Error response from daemon: experimental session with v1 builder is no longer supported, use builder version v2 (BuildKit) instead

Since this kernel is implementing lowering for a single TF operation, we
disable MLIR threading for efficiency purpose (avoid starting a large number
of threads eagerly).

This also caches the MLIRContext in the kernel so that repeated invocation won't lead to creating/destroying an MLIRContext.

[{"sha":"24c2e27256b8f2051bde626598f2fba34efd109b","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"DevTools Suspense cache cleanup (#22275)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/24c2e27256b8f2051bde626598f2fba34efd109b"},{"sha":"8f96c6b2ac3ff0e38f60c87b1f08deb9993526b5","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"[Bugfix] Prevent infinite update loop caused by a synchronous update in a passive effect (#22277)

* Add test that triggers infinite update loop

In 18, passive effects are flushed synchronously if they are the
result of a synchronous update. We have a guard for infinite update
loops that occur in the layout phase, but it doesn't currently work for
synchronous updates from a passive effect.

The reason this probably hasn't come up yet is because synchronous
updates inside the passive effect phase are relatively rare: you either
have to imperatively dispatch a discrete event, like `el.focus`, or you
have to call `ReactDOM.flushSync`, which triggers a warning. (In
general, updates inside a passive effect are not encouraged.)

I discovered this because `useSyncExternalStore` does sometimes
trigger updates inside the passive effect phase.

This commit adds a failing test to prove the issue exists. I will fix
it in the next commit.

* Fix failing test added in previous commit

The way we detect a "nested update" is if there's synchronous work
remaining at the end of the commit phase.

Currently this check happens before we synchronously flush the passive
effects. I moved it to after the effects are fired, so that it detects
whether synchronous work was scheduled in that phase.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/8f96c6b2ac3ff0e38f60c87b1f08deb9993526b5"},{"sha":"225740be4864ee8eeb349b38b329291450245578","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Add named hooks support to react-devtools-inline (#22263)

This commit builds on PR #22260 and makes the following changes:
* Adds a DevTools feature flag for named hooks support. (This allows us to disable it entirely for a build via feature flag.)
* Adds a new Suspense cache for dynamically imported modules. (This allows a component to suspend while importing an external code chunk– like the hook names parsing code).
* DevTools supports a hookNamesModuleLoaderFunction param to import the hook names module. I wish this could be handles as part of the react-devtools-shared package, but I'm not sure how to configure Webpack (4) to serve the chunk from react-devtools-inline. This seemed like a reasonable workaround.

The PR also contains an additional unrelated change:
* Removes pre-fetch optimization (added in DevTools: Improve named hooks network caching #22198). This optimization was mostly only important for cases where sources needed to be re-downloaded, something which we can now avoid in most cases¹ thanks to using cached responses already loaded by the page. (I tested this locally on Facebook and this change has no negative performance impact. There is still some overhead from serializing the JS through the Bridge but that's constant between the two approaches.)

¹ The case where we don't benefit from cached responses is when DevTools are opened after the page has already loaded certain scripts. This seems uncommon enough that I don't think it justified the added complexity of prefetching.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/225740be4864ee8eeb349b38b329291450245578"},{"sha":"96814e71b2ec13af64cd2670c9e69ab982ab2951","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Revert Suspense cache Thenable.catch() change (#22280)

`PyObject*` to `std::vector<T>` conversion logic:
- If user passed Numpy Array
  - If array is planar and T is a primitive type (doesn't require
    constructor call) that matches with the element type of array, then
    copy element one by one with the respect of the step between array
    elements. If compiler is lucky (or brave enough) copy loop can be
    vectorized.
    For classes that require constructor calls this path is not
    possible, because we can't begin an object lifetime without hacks.
  - Otherwise fall-back to general case
- Otherwise - execute the general case:
  If PyObject* corresponds to Sequence protocol - iterate over the
  sequence elements and invoke the appropriate `pyopencv_to` function.

`std::vector<T>` to `PyObject*` conversion logic:
- If `std::vector<T>` is empty - return empty tuple.
- If `T` has a corresponding `Mat` `DataType` than return
  Numpy array instance of the matching `dtype` e.g.
  `std::vector<cv::Rect>` is returned as `np.ndarray` of shape `Nx4` and
  `dtype=int`.
  This branch helps to optimize further evaluations in user code.
- Otherwise - execute the general case:
  Construct a tuple of length N = `std::vector::size` and insert
  elements one by one.

Unnecessary functions were removed and code was rearranged to allow
compiler select the appropriate conversion function specialization.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/AleksandrPanov/opencv/commits/16b95145439c509b9adb8600e0ff6dd83845f208"},{"sha":"edc442afdb559c7a8d731b86637839b5f224de35","author":{"name":"WJJ1995","email":"9d34c286e01f9cabbf4fd4eeb608c430de9c109d@163.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #20511 from wjj19950828:add_humanseg_support_0806

Change-Id: I2ff38f83c64b656a28a9a2950087c3b6f543a69a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/donny-stacks/tensorflow/commits/6a56f218c332ad66523ffe06f6060083f7ed5442"},{"sha":"098fc5e8c58ed0582cd0121839cddbff0a1c89d5","author":{"name":"Allen Lavoie","email":"eb65be0597eb1f51f240bbfc00f1cd10ccd2547c@google.com"},"message":"Pfor: Omit If ops in Gather's converter if the conditions are known statically

A downstream set_shape in pfor (setting vectorized_shape[1:] to original_shape) was causing issues for the branch of the cond statically known to not be taken.

There are some alternatives: we could remove the set_shape even though it's correct, or tweak If's gradient to discard extra shape information. Getting rid of the mismatch by omitting the branch known not to be taken (and therefore with conflicting shape information) seems simplest.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Roll out refcounting ResourceHandle to AnonymousResourceOp.

Only one user, AnonymousIteratorOpV2 is converted.

Associated fixes:

1. Release GIL when Eager dealloc calls into TF, which may call into Python from a different thread (Executor::Run always create a new thread).

2. Further trivialize TF_TensorFromTensor and TF_TensorToTensor, stop special treatment of DT_RESOURCE outside of the session Ops. (a step towards more cleanups near the TF_Tensor API)

The original motivation was to avoid calling into the (currently) undefined behavior of serializing a ref-counting ResourceHandle during SummarizeValue, which calls into these functions as part of TensorHandle::Resolve.

wangpeng and I agree that eventually upon / before serialization, Refcounting ResourceHandle shall register itself to the ResourceManager, with a unique name.
This will be done soon and the error message can be removed after that.

[{"sha":"8f96c6b2ac3ff0e38f60c87b1f08deb9993526b5","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"[Bugfix] Prevent infinite update loop caused by a synchronous update in a passive effect (#22277)

* Add test that triggers infinite update loop

In 18, passive effects are flushed synchronously if they are the
result of a synchronous update. We have a guard for infinite update
loops that occur in the layout phase, but it doesn't currently work for
synchronous updates from a passive effect.

The reason this probably hasn't come up yet is because synchronous
updates inside the passive effect phase are relatively rare: you either
have to imperatively dispatch a discrete event, like `el.focus`, or you
have to call `ReactDOM.flushSync`, which triggers a warning. (In
general, updates inside a passive effect are not encouraged.)

I discovered this because `useSyncExternalStore` does sometimes
trigger updates inside the passive effect phase.

This commit adds a failing test to prove the issue exists. I will fix
it in the next commit.

* Fix failing test added in previous commit

The way we detect a "nested update" is if there's synchronous work
remaining at the end of the commit phase.

Currently this check happens before we synchronously flush the passive
effects. I moved it to after the effects are fired, so that it detects
whether synchronous work was scheduled in that phase.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/facebook/react/commits/8f96c6b2ac3ff0e38f60c87b1f08deb9993526b5"}]

Change-Id: I766e734491c6733c5f5bd4a5e7e82da954e3a016","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/26bb0a3e52c74bc47725456753166c7a3a686cc3"},{"sha":"bb588f4b89355d46b10955922bdcf385075d286e","author":{"name":"Allen Lavoie","email":"eb65be0597eb1f51f240bbfc00f1cd10ccd2547c@google.com"},"message":"Allow tf.GradientTape to ignore forward-pass ops downstream of tf.stop_gradient

This will not change the numerics of tf.stop_gradient, just prevent some unneeded tf.function gradients from being built and reduce memory usage executing op-by-op (since tensors downstream of stop_gradient will no longer be `tape.watch`ed and held in memory unless there is another path to them).

Alternatively we could expose a tf.autodiff.stop_recording() context manager or something to that effect. We use that API a decent amount internally to avoid building gradient graphs / holding on to intermediates, so this seems like a good thing let people control one way or another.

Change-Id: Ic0e87bedb95893301da37191fc101fbc279e22ef","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/joshrose/tensorflow/commits/32f82e53099483da528987dd917392bd66c1770f"},{"sha":"86b1d613792d33f7c0d296ff84b11a3dad20faab","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[MLIR][KernelGen] Fix GPU module cache and make it a kernel resource

This fixes a subtle bug in the GPU module caches, which assumed that no two GPU
modules are loaded from the same memory location. When JIT-compiling kernels,
however, this can (and did) happen, which previously lead to a false cache hit,
resulting in the use of an incorrect GPU kernel.

Making the GPU module cache a kernel resource binds its lifetime to that of the
kernel context and also to that of the JIT cache....

Change-Id: Ia8fe5aad4d6d1f95b157ec35b110dba6242d709d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/joshrose/tensorflow/commits/6cfb888ddd2fe9ca93f1fc63cbdd30dffa6b2627"},{"sha":"a43f1c5e4dc3bd2955df13c844d0d7a6e8eac628","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"When determinism is enabled, raise error in tf.timestamp.

A FailedPrecondition error is raised. InvalidArgument is used for random ops when the seed isn't specified, but that doesn't apply here as there are no arguments.

tf.timestamp is mostly used to seed random ops. It is also occasionally used for measuring the performance of some part of the model. The latter case is a legitimate use case when determinism is used, but we must raise an error to guard against the former case.

[{"sha":"6f8c6dbdf7bf9155a931aaefb77fdbcff3b06e16","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Roll out refcounting ResourceHandle to AnonymousResourceOp.

Only one user, AnonymousIteratorOpV2 is converted.

Associated fixes:

1. Release GIL when Eager dealloc calls into TF, which may call into Python from a different thread (Executor::Run always create a new thread).

2. Further trivialize TF_TensorFromTensor and TF_TensorToTensor, stop special treatment of DT_RESOURCE outside of the session Ops. (a step towards more cleanups near the TF_Tensor API)

The original motivation was to avoid calling into the (currently) undefined behavior of serializing a ref-counting ResourceHandle during SummarizeValue, which calls into these functions as part of TensorHandle::Resolve.

wangpeng and I agree that eventually upon / before serialization, Refcounting ResourceHandle shall register itself to the ResourceManager, with a unique name.
This will be done soon and the error message can be removed after that.

Change-Id: Ic0e87bedb95893301da37191fc101fbc279e22ef","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/huaxz1986/tensorflow/commits/32f82e53099483da528987dd917392bd66c1770f"},{"sha":"86b1d613792d33f7c0d296ff84b11a3dad20faab","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[MLIR][KernelGen] Fix GPU module cache and make it a kernel resource

This fixes a subtle bug in the GPU module caches, which assumed that no two GPU
modules are loaded from the same memory location. When JIT-compiling kernels,
however, this can (and did) happen, which previously lead to a false cache hit,
resulting in the use of an incorrect GPU kernel.

Making the GPU module cache a kernel resource binds its lifetime to that of the
kernel context and also to that of the JIT cache....

Change-Id: Ia8fe5aad4d6d1f95b157ec35b110dba6242d709d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/huaxz1986/tensorflow/commits/6cfb888ddd2fe9ca93f1fc63cbdd30dffa6b2627"},{"sha":"a43f1c5e4dc3bd2955df13c844d0d7a6e8eac628","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"When determinism is enabled, raise error in tf.timestamp.

A FailedPrecondition error is raised. InvalidArgument is used for random ops when the seed isn't specified, but that doesn't apply here as there are no arguments.

tf.timestamp is mostly used to seed random ops. It is also occasionally used for measuring the performance of some part of the model. The latter case is a legitimate use case when determinism is used, but we must raise an error to guard against the former case.
